   +pod('A Survey of Spongiform Diseases')
      .uk-width-medium-5-10
         figure
            img.lg-no-shadow(src='images/brain.jpg', alt='Cross section of the brain')
            p
               | Diseases caused by prions are known as spongiform diseases, because the brain
               | tissue in infected individuals is filled with holes, giving it a sponge-like
               | appearance. Although prions are found throughout the brain, the symptoms of
               | spongiform diseases vary according to the regions they are most concentrated
               | in. There are currently no effective treatments for spongiform diseases and
               | all are fatal.
      .uk-width-medium-5-10
         p
            strong Classic CJD or Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (human)
         ul
            li The most prevalent of the spongiform diseases
            li Occurs spontaneously in 1 out of a million people
            li 10% of cases are inherited mutations in the PRPN gene
            li Usually strikes people age 50 to 75
            li Symptoms: dementia, muscle twitching, vision problems
         p
            strong Fatal Familial Insomnia (human)
         ul
            li All cases are inherited mutations in the PrP gene
            li Usually strikes people age 36 to 61
            li Disruption of sleep/wake cycle leads to coma, then death
         p
            strong Scrapie (goats, sheep)
         ul
            li Occurs as infection in genetically susceptible sheep
            li There is no evidence of spread to humans
         p
            strong BSE or Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy (cattle)
         ul
            li
               | Also known as &quot;Mad Cow Disease&quot; because infected animals act strangely and can be aggressive
            li Spread rapidly through Britain by rendering
         p
            strong Chronic Wasting Disease (deer, elk)
         ul
            li Infectious disease in wild deer and elk primarily in the western United States
            li Drooling, difficulty swallowing, weight loss
         p
            strong Kuru (human)
         ul
            li Struck members of the Fore tribe in the 1950s and 1960s
            li
               | Muscle weakness, loss of coordination, tremors, inappropriate episodes of laughter or crying
            li Transmitted by ritual cannibalism as part of funeral ceremonies
   +pod('The Controversy Behind Prions')
      .uk-width-medium-6-10
         p
            | The idea that a protein alone could transmit disease has been around since the 1960s.
            | New evidence has been stacking up to support this idea ever since.
         p
            | Ever since Stanley Prusiner coined the term prion in 1982 and showed that purified prions can transmit spongiform disease,
            | skeptics have been trying to prove him wrong. The idea that a protein can reproduce itself without going through
            | a nucleic acid intermediate goes against everything we know about transmissible diseases. Even the simplest
            | viruses contain genetic material, DNA or RNA, that codes for proteins necessary for function and transmission.
            | Because prions appear to be infectious proteins that can self-replicate, the central dogma of molecular biology,
            | (DNA to RNA to protein) seems not to apply here. So maybe these scientists are right to be skeptical.
            | Below are some of the reservations skeptics have about the protein-only hypothesis.
         h3 The strain phenomenon
         p
            | Scrapie and other spongiform diseases come in distinct strains that differ in their incubation period,
            | symptoms, and effects on different brain regions. Skeptics argue that these differences are due to mutations
            | in nucleic acid and is evidence that prions do indeed have genetic material.
         h3 Information from other amyloid diseases
         p
            | Alzheimer&apos;s disease, Parkinson&apos;s disease and Huntington&apos;s disease are also characterized by the
            | formation of misfolded protein into amyloid fibers, resulting in neurodegeneration. But these diseases
            | are not infectious, leading to the argument that misfolded protein alone is not enough to transmit disease.
         h3 Answering the skeptics
         p
            | The ultimate test of the protein-only hypothesis would be to produce PrP-res in a test tube,
            | inject it into a normal healthy brain, and show that spongiform disease results. In April 2005,
            | scientists at the University of Texas performed this experiment successfully showing that PrP-res
            | is indeed infectious. Questions still remain about what exactly triggers the folding of PrP-sen into PrP-res.
      .uk-width-medium-4-10
         figure
            img(src='images/oldmen.jpg', alt='men argument')
   +pod("You Can't Kill What Isn't Alive")
      .uk-width-medium-6-10
         p
            | Prions cannot be destroyed by boiling, alcohol, acid, standard autoclaving methods, or radiation.
            | In fact, infected brains that have been sitting in formaldehyde for decades can still transmit spongiform disease.
            | Cooking your burger &apos;til it&apos;s well done won&apos;t destroy the prions!
      .uk-width-medium-4-10.uk-text-center
         figure
            img.lg-no-shadow(src='images/brainBoiling.jpg', alt='Prions cannot be destroyed by boiling')

